Glaucus, said he, what cause think you is there
That we in Lycia more honour'd are Than other men, and look'd upon like Gods, And higher sit at feasts, and better fare, And drink best wine, and more land have by odds ?
Is't not because we foremost are in fight!
'Tis not in vain, they'll say, our princes have More honour, since they are of greater might, And their lives venture other men to save.
Glaucus, if we could death eschew and age
By running from the battle cowardly, D'ye think I foremost would myself engage, Or ever counsel you to follow me ?
You know the ways to death are infinite.
Though we ne'er fight we cannot always live.
Therefore come on, and let us bravely fight, And either honour gain, or honour give.
So said Sarpedon.
Glaucus him obey'd ;
And tow'rds the Greeks well followed they went.
