I am afraid Against these men I shall not able be To keep my place.
Keen warriors they are.
But if they be themselves distressed there, Let Telamonius of the place take care, And Teucer use his bow and arrows here.
Thootes then unto th' Ajaxes ran Along the Argive wall, and to them said, Mnesteus entreats both of you, if you can, To come unto his tow'r and give him aid.
Keen warriors, he says, these Lycians are:
But if you be yourselves distressed here, Let Telamonius of the place take care, And Teucer use his bow and arrows there.
This said, great Ajax said unto the less, Æliades, stay here awhile, till I Deliver Mnesteus from his distress.
That done, I shall be with you presently.
Ajax and Teucer then together go Unto the tow'r of Mnesteus with all speed, Pandion with them, carry'ng Teucer's bow, And at their coming found him in great need.
The Lycians, like a black and low'ring cloud, Ascended to the wall, and fiercely fought.
The Greeks resist.
