My mates, although I have endur'd much pain, I must entreat you patiently to hear;
We know not where is west or east, nor where The sun does rise or set, nor where we be;
To me does little hope as yet appear, And therefore we must go abroad and see.
In a low island, rising through the trees, I saw a smoke when I stood on the hill;
Though I had utter'd no more words but these, They heard them with a very evil will.
Of Cyclops and Antiphates they speak, That had devoured their fellows formerly:
And ready were their hearts with grief to break;
They weep and whine, but without remedy.
Of my companions then two bands I make;
Of one Eurylochus had the command, The charge o' th' other to myself I take:
And two-and-twenty men were in each band.
Who should go first abroad, and who should stay, We were content should be by lot defin'd;
To go, fell to Eurylochus.
